04349nam a22005895i 9780226810959DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021009479  a97802268109597 a10.7208/chicago/97802268109592doi  a(DE-B1597)606858  a(OCoLC)1264476972  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aML3917.F8bL53 2021 4aML3917 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a781.6509441 aLie, Siv B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDjango Generations :bHearing Ethnorace, Citizenship, and Jazz Manouche in France /cSiv B. Lie. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b4 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Ethnomusicology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNotes on Terminology -- tList of Figures -- tCompanion Website -- tIntroduction -- t1 Making Jazz Manouche -- t2 Cultural Activism’s Living Legacies -- t3 Generic Ontologies and the Stakes of Refusal -- t4 The Sound of Feeling -- t5 Heritage Stories -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix 1: Glossary -- tAppendix 2: List of Formal Interviews -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDjango Generations shows how relationships between racial identities, jazz, and national belonging become entangled in France. Jazz manouche—a genre known best for its energetic, guitar-centric swing tunes—is among France’s most celebrated musical practices of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. It centers on the recorded work of famed guitarist Django Reinhardt and is named for the ethnoracial subgroup of Romanies (also known, often pejoratively, as “Gypsies”) to which Reinhardt belonged. French Manouches are publicly lauded as bearers of this jazz tradition, and many take pleasure and pride in the practice while at the same time facing pervasive discrimination. Jazz manouche uncovers a contradiction at the heart of France’s assimilationist republican ideals: the music is portrayed as quintessentially French even as Manouches themselves endure treatment as racial others. In this book, Siv B. Lie explores how this music is used to construct divergent ethnoracial and national identities in a context where discussions of race are otherwise censured. Weaving together ethnographic and historical analysis, Lie shows that jazz manouche becomes a source of profound ambivalence as it generates ethnoracial difference and socioeconomic exclusion. As the first full-length ethnographic study of French jazz to be published in English, this book enriches anthropological, ethnomusicological, and historical scholarship on global jazz, race and ethnicity, and citizenship while showing how music can be an important but insufficient tool in struggles for racial and economic justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJazz musicianszFrance. 0aJazzxSocial aspectszFrance. 0aMusic and racezFrance. 0aMusicians, RomanizFrance. 0aRomaniesxMusicxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aRomaniesxMusicxSocial aspectszFrance. 0aRomanieszFrancexEthnic identity. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226810959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226810959/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles